---
import Layout from '../components/Layout.astro';
---

<Layout
  title="About"
  description="How OpenAgent.review selects papers and generates structured AI reviews next to arXiv abstracts."
  activeNav="about"
>
  <div class="page-header">
    <div class="container">
      <nav class="breadcrumb" aria-label="Breadcrumb">
        <a href="/">Home</a>
        <span class="sep">/</span>
        <span>About</span>
      </nav>
      <h1>About OpenAgent.review</h1>
      <p class="subtitle">
        A reading surface that pairs trending arXiv papers with a structured, conference-style AI review.
      </p>
    </div>
  </div>

  <div class="container about-trust-cards">
    <section class="about-callout">
      <h2 class="about-callout-heading">Key disclaimers</h2>
      <ul class="about-callout-list">
        <li>Reviews are single-pass language-model opinions, not peer review.</li>
        <li>Each review carries four dimension ratings (soundness / presentation / significance / originality), an overall recommendation, and an agent-confidence estimate. These are shown side-by-side, never averaged.</li>
        <li>The abstract shown is the author's own arXiv abstract, taken verbatim.</li>
        <li>The paper queue is driven by daily source feeds, not editorial selection.</li>
      </ul>
    </section>

    <section class="about-callout">
      <h2 class="about-callout-heading">Provenance</h2>
      <dl class="about-provenance-grid">
        <div>
          <dt>Source</dt>
          <dd>Hugging Face Trending Papers</dd>
        </div>
        <div>
          <dt>Method</dt>
          <dd>Structured language-model review on the arXiv PDF</dd>
        </div>
        <div>
          <dt>Update frequency</dt>
          <dd>On-trend, continuous — no fixed schedule</dd>
        </div>
      </dl>
    </section>
  </div>

  <div class="container">
    <section class="content prose-shell">
      <div class="prose prose--structured">
        <h2 id="what-this-is">What this is</h2>
        <p>
          OpenAgent.review is an experimental reading surface for trending research papers.
          For every paper we surface the arXiv abstract and a structured AI review — summary, four dimension ratings,
          key follow-up questions, and acknowledged limitations — all generated by a language model on the paper's PDF.
        </p>

        <h2 id="how-it-works">How the data flows</h2>
        <ul>
          <li>Papers are picked from <strong>Hugging Face Trending Papers</strong> as they surface.</li>
          <li>For each paper, the arXiv abstract is stored verbatim.</li>
          <li>A language model produces a structured review with four dimension scores (1–4 each),
              an overall recommendation (1–6), and a confidence estimate (1–5), plus prose fields
              for summary, strengths &amp; weaknesses, key questions, and limitations.</li>
          <li>The pair is published as JSON and rendered into a three-layer review page:
              speedread, four-dimension judgment, and raw-view audit.</li>
          <li>One review per paper. If the paper trends again later, we don't re-review it.</li>
        </ul>

        <h2 id="rubric">The rubric</h2>
        <p>Borrowed from conference-style reviews, the four dimensions are:</p>
        <ul>
          <li><strong>Soundness</strong> — are the claims supported by the evidence?</li>
          <li><strong>Presentation</strong> — is the paper clearly written and well structured?</li>
          <li><strong>Significance</strong> — does it address an important or relevant problem?</li>
          <li><strong>Originality</strong> — does it provide new insights, data, or perspectives?</li>
        </ul>
        <p>
          Each dimension is scored 1–4 (poor → excellent) and carries a short justification.
          The overall recommendation uses the 1–6 Strong Reject → Strong Accept scale.
          The agent also produces a confidence score (1–5) reflecting how sure it is about its own evaluation.
        </p>

        <h2 id="limits">What this isn't</h2>
        <ul>
          <li>Not peer review, not an editorial endorsement, not a publication decision.</li>
          <li>Reviews are single-pass model outputs with no human verification.</li>
          <li>No author rebuttal flow — readers follow the arXiv link if they want the full paper.</li>
        </ul>

        <h2 id="faq">FAQ</h2>
        <h3>Why aren't the four dimension scores averaged?</h3>
        <p>
          Averaging hides the shape of the reasoning. A paper might be
          significant but poorly presented, or technically sound but incremental in
          originality. Collapsing those into one number pretends those differences
          don't matter; they do.
        </p>

        <h3>Is this peer review?</h3>
        <p>No. It is a lightweight AI reading aid. Use the source link to check the paper yourself.</p>

        <h3>How are papers picked?</h3>
        <p>
          We watch the Hugging Face Trending Papers feed. When a paper we haven't reviewed
          shows up, the pipeline fires a review for it. No fixed daily quota, no editorial
          calendar — the feed ebbs and flows with what's trending.
        </p>

        <h3>Why was this paper selected?</h3>
        <p>
          Because it was trending on Hugging Face at some point after the site went live,
          and we hadn't reviewed it yet. There's no venue-specific editorial selection.
        </p>

        <h3>Can the review be wrong?</h3>
        <p>Yes. Treat the opinion as a first-pass impression. The abstract and paper link are always one click away, and every detail page ships a raw-view toggle so you can read the agent's original prose without our structuring.</p>

        <h2 id="colophon">Colophon</h2>
        <p>
          Built with <a href="https://astro.build" target="_blank" rel="noopener">Astro</a>,
          with a static shell, hand-written CSS, and a small amount of client-side enhancement.
          Math rendering uses <a href="https://katex.org" target="_blank" rel="noopener">KaTeX</a>.
        </p>
      </div>
      <aside class="prose-toc" aria-label="On this page">
        <span class="prose-toc-label">On this page</span>
        <ol>
          <li><a href="#what-this-is">What this is</a></li>
          <li><a href="#how-it-works">How the data flows</a></li>
          <li><a href="#rubric">The rubric</a></li>
          <li><a href="#limits">What this isn't</a></li>
          <li><a href="#faq">FAQ</a></li>
          <li><a href="#colophon">Colophon</a></li>
        </ol>
      </aside>
    </section>
  </div>
</Layout>
